before_annotation.answer:
The following beautifully simple version of Rubinstein's proof of uniqueness is from Shaked and Sutton 1984.
Suppose player 1 makes the offer at some date. Because player 2 gets at most $\bar{V}_2$ in the next period
(perfectness requires that equilibrium is also sustained from the next period on), the offer $x_1$ such that
$1-x_1=\delta\bar{V}_2$ is accepted. Hence,
\begin{equation}
\underline{V}_1 \ge x_1 = 1-\delta\bar{V}_2. \tag{11.24}
\end{equation}

Similarly, the most player 1 can get now is $\bar{V}_1 \le 1-\underline{W}_2$;
but $\underline{W}_2 \ge \delta \underline{V_2}$, because player 2 can always reject and wait for his turn. Hence,
\begin{equation}
\bar{V}_1 \le 1-\delta \underline{V_2}. \tag{11.25}
\end{equation}

Similar equations hold when player 2 makes the offer:
\begin{equation}
\underline{V}_2 \ge 1-\delta\bar{V}_1. \tag{11.26}
\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
\bar{V}_2 \le 1-\delta\underline{V}_1. \tag{11.27}
\end{equation}

Now 11.24 and 11.27 give
\begin{equation}
\underline{V}_1 \ge 1-\delta+\delta^2\underline{V}_1
\Rightarrow \underline{V}_1 \ge \frac{1}{1+\delta}. \tag{11.28}
\end{equation}
and 11.25 and 11.26 give
\begin{equation}
\bar{V}_1 \le 1-\delta+\delta^2\bar{V}_1
\Rightarrow \bar{V}_1 \le \frac{1}{1+\delta}. \tag{11.29}
\end{equation}

Because $\underline{V}_1 \le \bar{V}_1$ by definition,
\[
\underline{V}_1=\bar{V}_1=V_1=\frac{1}{1+\delta}.
\]
Similarly,
\[
\underline{W}_1=\bar{W}_1=W_1=\frac{\delta}{1+\delta}.
\]
The same equations hold for player 2. Since valuations are unique, it is easy to see that the equilibrium strategies
are also unique, and that they are those described in the text.

